properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected Sunday afternoon and evening. A low pressure system will move across southern BC Sunday spreading snow to the interior. At the same time, the arctic front will arrive with strong gusty winds and dropping temperatures. These winds are expected to rise late in the morning and remain strong through the afternoon and evening. The combination of falling snow with very strong winds will result in blowing snow and poor visibility. The worst conditions are expected through the afternoon and evening, Visibility will improve through the night as snow tapers off and winds ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy snowfall with blowing snow is expected. Snow continues this morning with additional 2 to 5 cm. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 20 cm are expected in many areas, with locally higher amounts near 25 cm possible in a few locales especially in the North Bay and Nipissing areas by late this morning. In addition, strong northeast winds gusting to 60 km/h will whip up freshly fallen snow with frequent very low to nil visibility in blowing snow especially in exposed areas. The winter storm will end late this morning as the moisture laden Texas low moves away from the Great Lakes area. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. The rain will change over to freezing rain early this morning as temperatures dip to near the zero degree mark. Freezing rain warnings are in effect for areas just north and east of Toronto, and may be extended into areas from Toronto and west as needed. Brisk northwest winds gusting up to 60 km/h will herald the end of the precipitation later this morning. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry district office. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 10 cm is expected. The snow will continue through the night and end near noon on Sunday. A total of 10 cm of snow is forecast by noon on Sunday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
